    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-09T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-09T07:00:00-05:00" n="124"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d124">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 793.94/288.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Reinsch</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-09T20:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 9, 1915—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At yesterday’s meeting residence in Manchuria was further discussed, China
                    holding that taxes and police regulations should apply equally to Japan,
                    Japanese residents and Chinese citizens, while the Japanese demanded the right
                    of veto in these matters.</p>
                <p>Passing to Group V, Japanese Minister presented a paper containing an additional
                    demand in Fukien namely the concession of coal mines at Anki. The Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs refused to receive this document stating that his Government
                    could not enter upon a discussion of any demands in Group V or in extension
                    thereof as they were inconsistent with national independence and treaty
                    obligations. * * * Japanese Minister withdrew the paper and declared that he
                    could only report the attitude of the Chinese Government to his own.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
